    The root cause of the crash is a stack buffer overflow due to an            
    off-by-one error in the crc8 function.                                      
                                                                                
    Step-by-step Analysis                                                       
                                                                                
     1 Function call in main:                                                   
                                                                                
        uint8_t c = crc8(buf, sizeof(buf));                                     
                                                                                
        • buf is a local array of 7 bytes: uint8_t buf[7] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x03,  
          0x04, 0x05, 0x06, 0x07};                                              
        • sizeof(buf) is 7, so len = 7 is passed to crc8.                       
     2 Inside crc8:                                                             
                                                                                
        for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) {                                     
            crc ^= buf[i];                                                      
                                                                                
        • The loop condition is i <= len, which means i will go from 0 to 7     
          (inclusive).                                                          
        • Since buf is of size 7, valid indices are 0 to 6.                     
        • When i == 7, this accesses buf[7], which is one byte past the end of  
          the array — out-of-bounds memory access.                              
     3 Why this causes a stack buffer overflow:                                 
        • In C, accessing memory past the bounds of a local array (like buf)    
          leads to undefined behavior.                                          
        • Because buf is allocated on the stack, reading buf[7] reads from an   
          adjacent memory location (possibly on the stack frame of main or a    
          nearby variable).                                                     
        • This is considered a stack buffer overflow in the context of a        
          security vulnerability, even though the access is not necessarily     
          exploitable here (e.g., no obvious compromise of control flow).       
        • The behavior is undefined — it may crash, corrupt data, or silently   
          continue.                                                             
     4 Debugging the program state:                                             
        • Running frame variable returned no output — this likely means the     
          debugger could not retrieve local variables, which is suspicious.     
          This often happens when the program has already crashed or memory is  
          corrupted.                                                            
        • The print buf command returned 0x0000000000000000, which is           
          incorrect — this suggests the memory for buf may have been corrupted  
          or the debugger lost track (e.g., due to stack corruption from the    
          invalid read).                                                        
        • Attempts to print len and i failed — again due to possibly corrupted  
          stack state or the program crashing.                                  
     5 Root cause:                                                              
        • The loop condition i <= len is incorrect.                             
        • The loop should run len times, for i = 0 to len - 1, inclusive.       
        • Instead, the loop runs one extra time, accessing buf[len] = buf[7],   
          which is invalid.                                                     
     6 Corroboration:                                                           
        • The comment in the source is explicit: /* BUG: the loop bound is      
          inclusive — reads buf[len], which is one past the last valid byte.    
          */                                                                    
        • This confirms the developer already identified the issue.             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Fix                                                                         
                                                                                
    ✅ Minimal Local Fix:                                                       
                                                                                
    Change the loop condition from i <= len to i < len.                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {                      
         uint8_t crc = 0x00;                                                    
         for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {  // Fixed: i < len instead of i     
     <= len                                                                     
             crc ^= buf[i];                                                     
             for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {                                      
                 crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07) :            
     (uint8_t)(crc << 1);                                                       
             }                                                                  
         }                                                                      
         return crc;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This immediately fixes the off-by-one bug and prevents the out-of-bounds    
    access.                                                                     
                                                                                
    🔍 More Thorough Root-Cause Fix:                                            
                                                                                
    While the minimal fix resolves the immediate issue, a more robust fix       
    includes:                                                                   
                                                                                
     • Using size_t consistently for length.                                    
     • Adding a check to avoid calling with len == 0 or negative lengths        
       (though size_t is unsigned).                                             
     • Ensuring buf is not NULL (add a guard if needed):                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {                      
         if (buf == NULL) {                                                     
             return 0;                                                          
         }                                                                      
         uint8_t crc = 0x00;                                                    
         for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {                                     
             crc ^= buf[i];                                                     
             for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {                                      
                 crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07) :            
     (uint8_t)(crc << 1);                                                       
             }                                                                  
         }                                                                      
         return crc;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This improves robustness and prevents potential crashes from invalid        
    inputs (even though the current main does not call with NULL).              
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Fix the loop condition in crc8 from i <= len to i < len.                 
     2 Add a null pointer check for robustness, especially if the function is   
       used in a larger system.                                                 
     3 Avoid similar off-by-one errors by using static analysis tools (like     
       clang-tidy, valgrind, or address sanitizer) during development.          
                                                                                
